video:video.video:description: Paetongtarn Shinawatra was suspended from the role of Thailand's prime minister last month by the court pending an ethics investigation into a leaked phone call with senior Cambodia politician Hun Sen, which was perceived as damaging to Thailand’s interests and image.

video:video.video:title: Zelenskyy thanks Trump multiple times during meeting
video:video.video:description: In February, U.S. Vice President J.D. Vance clashed with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy in the Oval Office, when he accused the Ukrainian leader of not thanking the U.S. for its support in their fight against the Russian invasion.

video:video.video:title: Expert on why an Alaskan U.S. military base is a win-win summit spot for both Putin and Trump
video:video.video:description: In an ironic twist, President Donald Trump is set to discuss the war in Ukraine with Russian leader Vladimir Putin at a military base in Alaska that was crucial to countering the Soviet Union during the height of Cold War and still plays a role today.

video:video.video:title: Robot soccer teams prepare for the World Humanoid Robot Games in Beijing
video:video.video:description: Thirty robot teams from countries such as the United States, Brazil, Germany, and Portugal have been registered to play in the soccer competition, according to the organizer.

video:video.video:title: Qatar and Egypt seek to restart Israel-Hamas ceasefire talks
video:video.video:description: Egyptian Foreign Minister Bader Abdelattay said on Monday that his Qatari counterpart Sheikh Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al Thani arrived in Cairo and joined talks on restarting ceasefire negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian militant group Hamas.

video:video.video:title: Palestinians return from the Zikim area with aid after famine declaration
video:video.video:description: Palestinians were seen coming and going from the Zikim area on Saturday, where they were seeking aid from trucks entering with supplies, a day after the world's leading authority on food crises said the Gaza Strip's largest city was gripped by famine.

video:video.video:title: What's the most climate-friendly way to travel 200 miles?
video:video.video:description: Train, plane or car? Your weekend trip could burn triple the carbon, depending on how you get there. (AP Video: Kiki Sideris)

video:video.video:title: DC Attorney General expects city to retain police leadership for now
video:video.video:description: Washington DC's top attorney, Brian Schwalb, told reporters he expects the federal government to agree that the city police chief remains in charge of the department, at least for the coming days.

video:video.video:title: Zelenskyy says Russia's bombardment of Kyiv shows Putin wants to continue war
video:video.video:description: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said on Thursday Russia's major aerial attack on Kyiv shows President Vladimir Putin is "choosing ballistics" instead of "real steps towards peace".

video:video.video:title: Hundreds of people evacuate from Gaza City
video:video.video:description: Hundreds of people, who fled Gaza City, were moving south on Friday, seeking safety as Israel launched what it called the "initial stages" of a planned offensive in the city.

video:video.video:title: Palestinians rush to get aid from airdrops as Israel's plans to launch new operation in Gaza advance
video:video.video:description: In the central area of Nuseirat, scores of people scuffled after a military cargo plane dropped dozens of containers of aid.
